Docling is the preferred ingest engine for ITAP apps because of the robustness of processing tables, and their choice to embed graphics

It is instructive to read why IBM made the choice to embed the graphics.

IBM's decision to embed graphics in Docling stems from the need to make document processing more comprehensive and AI-ready. By incorporating graphics handling capabilities, Docling addresses several key challenges in document analysis:

1. Preserving Visual Context: Many documents, especially in business settings, contain crucial information in the form of images, charts, and diagrams. By embedding graphics, Docling ensures that this visual context is not lost during the document parsing process[1][2].

2. Enhancing AI Understanding: Modern AI models, particularly large language models (LLMs), are increasingly capable of processing and understanding visual information. By including graphics, Docling allows these models to gain a more complete understanding of the document's content[2].

3. Improving Data Extraction: Tables, charts, and other graphical elements often contain valuable data that might be difficult to extract using traditional text-based methods. Docling's ability to handle these elements allows for more comprehensive data extraction[1][2].

4. Facilitating Multimodal AI Applications: As AI applications evolve to handle both text and visual data, having a tool that can process both simultaneously becomes increasingly valuable. This capability positions Docling as a versatile tool for developing multimodal AI applications[1][7].

5. Streamlining Document Conversion: By handling both text and graphics in a single pass, Docling simplifies the process of converting complex documents into formats that are easily digestible by AI models, such as JSON or Markdown[10].

6. Supporting Enterprise Use Cases: Many enterprise documents, such as annual reports, technical manuals, and presentations, heavily rely on visual elements. Docling's graphics capabilities make it particularly well-suited for processing these types of documents[2][8].

By embedding graphics capabilities in Docling, IBM has created a more robust and versatile tool for document processing, aligning with the growing trend towards multimodal AI applications and more comprehensive document analysis in enterprise settings.
